<h1 align="center">Introduction to Linux</h1>

What is Linux?

- Linux is an operating system, just like Windows or macOS, but it is free for anyone to use. You
  can even see its source code and change it if you want. It was created in 1991 by Linus Torvalds.
- To understand Linux easily, think of it as a system that helps your computer work. It connects
  the hardware (like CPU, memory, keyboard) with the software (apps and programs).
- At the center of Linux is the kernel. This is the most important part because it directly talks to
  the hardware and controls everything.
- Linux also comes with built-in tools (commands) that help you do tasks like creating files,
  copying data, or searching text. These are called GNU tools and are mostly used through the
  terminal.
- There are also libraries, which are like ready-made code that programs use so developers don’t
  have to write everything from scratch.
- If you don’t like typing commands, Linux also has graphical interfaces called desktop
  environments. These give you windows, icons, and menus, just like other operating systems.

Where Linux is Used?

- Linux is used in many places, even if you don’t notice it.
- Most websites and online services run on Linux servers because it is stable and can handle heavy
  work without crashing.
- In cloud platforms like AWS or Google Cloud, Linux is widely used to run virtual machines and
  applications.
- If you are using an Android phone, you are already using Linux, because Android is built on the
  Linux kernel.
- Linux is also used in small devices like routers, smart TVs, and smart home devices because it is
  lightweight and reliable.
- Even supercomputers use Linux because it is powerful and efficient for large calculations.

What is an Operating System (OS)?

- An operating system is the main software that runs your computer.
- It acts like a bridge between you and the hardware. Without it, your computer cannot run
  programs.
- When you open an app, the operating system decides how much memory it should use and when
  it should run. It also allows multiple programs to run at the same time smoothly.
- It organizes your files so you can store and find them easily.
- It also controls devices like your keyboard, mouse, and internet connection.
- Another important job is security. It makes sure only the right users can access certain files or
  perform important actions.

Linux Kernel:

- The kernel is the core part of Linux.
- It directly communicates with the hardware and manages everything happening inside the system.
- Whenever a program needs something, like memory or access to a file, it asks the kernel. The
  kernel then handles the request.
- It decides which program should use the CPU and for how long.
- It also manages memory, making sure programs don’t interfere with each other.
- The kernel also works with device drivers so your system can use hardware like USB devices,
  graphics cards, and networks.
- Simply put, the kernel is the engine, and the operating system is the full car (engine + tools +
  interface).

Linux Kernel Type:

- Linux uses something called a monolithic kernel.
- This means most of the important system services run inside the kernel itself.
- Because everything is connected closely, Linux can work very fast and efficiently.
- It can also load extra features (like drivers) when needed without restarting the whole system.
- However, if something goes wrong inside the kernel, it can affect the entire system.
- There is another type called a microkernel, where services run separately. That design is more
  stable but usually slower.
- Linux focuses more on speed and performance, which is why it uses a monolithic kernel.

Linux Characteristics:

Open Source

- Linux is open-source, which means anyone can see how it is built and even change it. This is one
  of the biggest reasons why Linux is so popular.
- Developers around the world continuously improve it, fix bugs, and add new features. Because
  of this community support, Linux keeps getting better and more secure over time.
- Another important thing is freedom. You are not locked into one version. You can customize
  Linux the way you want or even create your own version based on your needs.

Multi-user

- Linux allows multiple users to use the same system at the same time without interfering with
  each other.
- Each user has their own account, files, and permissions. This means one user cannot randomly
  access or change another user’s data.
- There is also a special user called root, who has full control over the system. Regular users have
  limited access, which helps protect the system from accidental or harmful changes.

