Multitasking

- Linux can run many programs at the same time without slowing down or crashing.
- For example, you can run a server, edit files, and download something all at once. The system
  manages all these tasks in the background and gives each one a fair share of CPU time.
- Even if one program stops working, it usually won’t affect others. This makes Linux very
  reliable for heavy workloads.

Portability

- Linux can run on many different types of devices, from powerful computers to small gadgets.
- The same Linux system can work on desktops, servers, smartphones, and even devices like
  routers or smart TVs.
- This is possible because Linux is designed to work with different hardware using drivers. So it
  can easily adapt to new environments.

Security

- Linux is known for being very secure, mainly because of how it controls access.
- Every file and program has permissions, which decide who can read, write, or execute it. This
  prevents unauthorized access.
- Only the root user can perform critical system changes. Regular users must ask for permission
  (using special commands) to perform such tasks.
- Linux also keeps processes separate, so if one program has an issue, it does not affect the whole
  system.

Stability

- Linux is extremely stable and can run for a long time without restarting.
- If one program crashes, the rest of the system usually keeps running without problems. This is
  why Linux is widely used in servers and important systems.
- It is designed to handle heavy workloads smoothly, making it reliable for long-term use.

Linux Architecture

Layered Structure

- Linux is designed in layers. Each layer has its own job and works with the layer next to it.
- This design makes the system easier to manage, more secure, and more stable.

Hardware Layer

- This is the physical part of the computer, like the CPU, memory, storage, and input/output
  devices.
- Linux itself does not directly depend on hardware. Instead, it uses drivers to communicate with
  these components.

Kernel Layer

- The kernel is the core of Linux and controls everything happening in the system.
- It manages processes, memory, devices, and files. Whenever a program needs something, it goes
  through the kernel.
- The kernel makes sure all parts of the system work together properly and efficiently.

System Call Interface

- Programs cannot directly access hardware. Instead, they request services from the kernel.
- This is done through system calls, which act like a safe communication bridge between
- applications and the kernel.
- For example, when a program wants to open or read a file, it sends a request through this
  interface, and the kernel handles it.

Shell

- The shell is where users interact with Linux using commands.
- It takes your command, understands it, and tells the kernel what to do. Then it shows you the
  result.

Common Commands

Command Why it is used

